## Executive Summary

The Netherlands Ministry of Foreign Affairs is a significant
humanitarian donor, contributing an average of \$27 million annually
with a strong upward funding trend and expanding geographic reach—from 8
to 16 recipient countries (2022-2025). Its funding prioritizes global
initiatives, allocating the largest share to broad, multi-regional
programs, while maintaining moderate earmarking levels (around 25%),
offering a balance of flexibility and targeted support. Funding
volatility and lower transaction frequency relative to peers indicate
potential for increasing transaction regularity to enhance
predictability. Humanitarian actors should align proposals with the
Netherlands’ preference for global-scale projects and capitalize on its
strategic regional shifts to optimize partnership and resource
mobilization.

## Volatility

This chart presents the funding volatility of the Netherlands Ministry
of Foreign Affairs, showing transaction values in USD over time from May
2023 to December 2025. The data includes 115 transactions averaging 1.9
million USD each with an average of 38.3 transactions per year. Compared
to top 10 donors benchmark, which average 2.9 million USD per
transaction and 371.3 transactions per year, the Netherlands
demonstrates substantially lower transaction frequency and smaller
average transaction sizes. The trend line and ribbon indicate
fluctuations with periods of increased funding activity but generally
lower transaction volume. This pattern suggests opportunities to
diversify and increase funding flows for sustained humanitarian impact.
For proposal design, consider targeting higher transaction frequency to
improve predictability and program continuity. Fundraising strategies
could emphasize bridging transaction gaps and leveraging benchmarks from
top donors to enhance funding attractiveness. Clear funding continuity
is key to effective operational planning and improved aid delivery.
